  "sourceType": "CLASSIC",
  "sourceNotes": "Cherry pie appears in American domestic cookery from the nineteenth century, associated with the cherry-growing regions of the Midwest (Michigan, Washington State). Fannie Farmer, The Boston Cooking-School Cook Book (1896), gives a cherry pie recipe with a standard pastry; the lattice-top form appears throughout American domestic baking manuals of the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Fresh sweet cherries make a noticeably better filling than frozen, but frozen pitted cherries are an effective substitute outside the season.",
